         <abstract>
            <p>It is an open conjecture that for any positive odd integer $m$ the function $$C(m) = (3m + 1)/2^{e(m)},$$ where $e(m)$ is chosen so that $C(m)$ is again an odd integer, satisfies $C^h(m) = 1$ for some $h$. Here we show that the number of $m \leqslant x$ which satisfy the conjecture is at least $x^c$ for a positive constant $c$. A connection between the validity of the conjecture and the diophantine equation $2^x - 3^y = p$ is established. It is shown that if the conjecture fails due to an occurence $m = C^k(m)$, then $k$ is greater than 17985. Finally, an analogous "$qx + r$" problem is settled for certain pairs $(q, r) \neq (3, 1)$.</p>
          </abstract>
